{
  "texts": [
    "M, x ⊩ ¬φ iff ∀x ′ ⊑ x: if x ′ ̸ = ⊥, then M, x ′ ⊮ φ.",
    "◁Now an easy induction shows that all formulas are true at the impossible state ⊥, using the fact that in an extended model, every p ∈ Φ is true at ⊥ given the requirement that ⊥ ∈ P. It is also easy to see that Fact 4.18 does not hold for extended possibility models.As a natural example of an extended possibility frame, we have the following.",
    "⊥ = ⟨S, ⊑, ⊥, {R i } i∈I, P ⟩ and M ℘ ⊥ = ⟨F ℘, π⟩, are defined by: S = ℘(W); X ⊑ Y iff X ⊆ Y; ⊥ = ∅; XR i Y iff Y ⊆ R i [X]; P = {↓X | X ∈ A}; and π(p) = {X ∈ S | X ⊆ V(p)}.",
    "Note that if F is a Kripke frame, then P = {↓X | X ∈ S}.",
    "◁We can switch back and forth between extended and non-extended frames whenever convenient, by restriction as in Definition 4.19 and extension as in Definition 4.23.Definition 4.23 (Extending Frames)."
  ]
}